There's no endpoint to give an estimate of compute units per chute.  You can look at this one: https://api.chutes.ai/chutes/utilization which has the total invocations and busy ratio, and then use the chutes endpoint to get the compute multiplier and the number of instances per chute, then do 1 / (current number of instances + 1) to estimate your share if invocation counts.  Busy ratio here is roughly the concurrency, so for example a busy ratio of 4.7 means the chute had 4.7 ongoing requests concurrently for each and every instance for the entire past day, so your compute units would be (roughly, because it's normalized by performance and such) the number of seconds in a day * concurrency * compute_multiplier for the chute.

openrouter calls the validator via base URL https://llm.chutes.ai/v1  and we route to miners. Miners are never directly exposed.  Comms are https to validator, custom encryption (aes-256 based) to miner nodes.  Request metadata is logged and stored in invocations database and we have datadog logging (which again, not request body just metadata), but we don't store prompt data/payload, just the user id, timestamps, metrics (tps, ttft, etc.). Here's a lengthier explanation and perhaps this will also give more light as to the reason.

We have ~9400 GPUs online, and instances are created about once per minute.  Most instances, at least the ones that get created frequently, are naturally the larger/higher demand models, which require 8 GPUs.  It takes approximately 30 seconds for a single iteration of the graval challenge on an h200, and obviously for b200 and AMD mi300x/etc with more VRAM it will take longer, and ideally we do more than one iteration, which means to validate 8 GPUs, we need 30 seconds * 8 GPUs * (N iterations) of compute time.  At the least computationally expensive version it is one iteration so we'll call it 4 minutes of compute by the validator for every minute online due to instance creation rate, and we have limited capacity so if there's an immediate urgent model scale issue we can't accomodate (e.g. when deepseek-r2 is released).  More scale = more validation compute = huge bottleneck.

It's a bit of a process (and obviously very expensive) to add additional capacity to GPU validation, particularly with zero take on the validator (which helps ensure our validator gets the bulk of stake and maintain operations as the basis of vtrust for the others etc.). So, instead, we can now additionally run the GraVal challenges on miner nodes, where the validator continuously checks *those* chutes for accuracy to ensure no manipulation is found, thereby unlocking much higher scale of the platform.  Hierarchical validation so our validator doesn't need to run dozens of blackwell chips.

Chutes is really the perfect solution to the entire thing, because it solves exactly what the issue is. Compute on demand that scales with demand.

Additionally, to cut down on the cost and compute requirements, we have historically cached the final challenge matrix on the validator GPU nodes and re-used the challenge seed that was used when the GPU/node was initially added. The issue is, since the seed is currently deterministic/consistent, it's possible to play games with bounties and things of that sort, because you can spin up a chute with the known seed and just wait to activate it until that chute goes cold. It's not a widespread problem, really, but it's also something that shouldn't be possible, given sufficient compute to use fresh seeds each and every time. The updated code which I'm hoping to finish up today (or was anyways, maybe not with the chain issues...) prevents a chute from starting up in this manner, i.e. you get a JWT when you wish to deploy a chute, that JWT is exchanged for a graval challenge with random seed, etc., the challenge is solved and only at that point can the instance be activated.
